7ade63c927a8"],

Cell[TextData[{
 StyleBox["Figure 1:",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 " Numerical Fourier transform. Note that in this example there were ~33% \
more pixels sampling the Fourier transform than sampling the original \
function, the Fourier transformed function is shifted from numerical center, \
and the frequency axis has been \[OpenCurlyQuote]zoomed\[CloseCurlyQuote] in \
on."
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.7565855407741613`*^9, 3.75658560111932*^9}, {
  3.756920546676746*^9, 
  3.756920599527993*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"ff0251ad-7621-40e9-8f58-\
772ed80e668f"],

Cell[TextData[{
 StyleBox["Questions:\n",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 "\nAnswer the following questions about this form of the Fourier transform:\n\
\n1) What are the advantages of calculating the Fourier transform in this \
way?\n\n2) What are some disadvantages?\n\n3) What happens when ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    SubscriptBox["f", 
     RowBox[{"x", "\[InvisibleComma]", "Max"}]], ">", 
    FractionBox["1", "\[CapitalDelta]x"]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "33443149-b500-424b-be88-cbd23d2fde8b"],
 "?  Give an explanation for this behavior. ",
 StyleBox["HINT",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 ": looking at an extreme case where ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    SubscriptBox["f", 
     RowBox[{"x", "\[InvisibleComma]", "Max"}]], "=", 
    FractionBox["2", "\[CapitalDelta]x"]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "fbc5a9c9-46e2-45ed-8a59-5286684b7c7b"],
 " is useful.\n\n4) Is power always conserved (in a \
Parseval\[CloseCurlyQuote]s theorem manner) for this transform?"
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{
  3.75657975140928*^9, {3.756579904036889*^9, 3.756579938297516*^9}, 
   3.756580342881638*^9, {3.7565836510877457`*^9, 3.756583681737048*^9}, {
   3.756584487329117*^9, 3.7565844956404467`*^9}, {3.7565846180508423`*^9, 
   3.756584618939209*^9}, {3.756584719530713*^9, 3.756584756903268*^9}, {
   3.756585314364695*^9, 3.756585320116394*^9}, {3.7565855141068773`*^9, 
   3.756585520198162*^9}, {3.7569138889027*^9, 3.756913893115543*^9}, {
   3.75691960134204*^9, 3.756919602137054*^9}, {3.7569203030209713`*^9, 
   3.7569203072052097`*^9}, 3.756957943158402*^9},
 FontWeight->"Regular",
 Background->RGBColor[
  0.87, 0.94, 1],ExpressionUUID->"84946d60-6c21-4160-a975-9f29ce9bca60"],

Cell[TextData[StyleBox["1.2 Normalized Fast Fourier Transform algorithm (FFT)",
 FontWeight->"Bold"]], "Text",
 FontSize->14,
 FontWeight->"Regular",ExpressionUUID->"30d38386-f855-40a2-bd4f-a2d2f18a08bd"],

Cell["\<\
The goal of this simple exercise is to modify Matlab\[CloseCurlyQuote]s built \
in FFT function so that: 1) it conserves power in a \
Parseval\[CloseCurlyQuote]s manner and 2) it performs the correct grid \
shifting so that the zero-frequency component appears at the center of the \
grid. The result will be (at least) two new, custom functions. Because you \
will be using these functions throughout the course of the semester I suggest \
you call them something concise such as, \[OpenCurlyQuote]nfft1\
\[CloseCurlyQuote], and \[OpenCurlyQuote]nifft1\[CloseCurlyQuote] or \
\[OpenCurlyQuote]nfft2\[CloseCurlyQuote], and \[OpenCurlyQuote]nifft2\
\[CloseCurlyQuote] where the \[OpenCurlyQuote]n\[CloseCurlyQuote] stands for \
normalized, or any other reasonable name.

The help documentation on Matlab\[CloseCurlyQuote]s version of the FFT is \
helpful for this process:\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.756557377230928*^9, 3.756557446978877*^9}, {
   3.756557556914289*^9, 3.756557562958906*^9}, {3.756557729260766*^9, 
   3.75655773004984*^9}, {3.756560677467579*^9, 3.756560695134346*^9}, 
   3.7565803912462*^9, {3.7565845271894913`*^9, 3.756584543122981*^9}, {
   3.756837116936119*^9, 3.7568371169997663`*^9}, {3.756910638503682*^9, 
   3.756910739836038*^9}, {3.7569108983392487`*^9, 3.7569109598982286`*^9}, {
   3.756911027210867*^9, 3.7569110350867*^9}, {3.7569114831886168`*^9, 
   3.756911590597681*^9}, {3.7569117949153643`*^9, 3.756911809721245*^9}, {
   3.7569120354357862`*^9, 3.756912063251766*^9}, {3.7569124546205597`*^9, 
   3.756912473357703*^9}, {3.756912905606782*^9, 3.756912943710284*^9}, {
   3.756920768041636*^9, 3.7569207684651823`*^9}},
 FontWeight->"Regular",ExpressionUUID->"3b3d29ba-7021-44c1-b1bd-e04cf18a075a"],

