    255},
    ColorFunction->RGBColor],
   BoxForm`ImageTag["Byte", ColorSpace -> "RGB", Interleaving -> True],
   Selectable->False],
  DefaultBaseStyle->"ImageGraphics",
  ImageSize->{905.935156250001, Automatic},
  ImageSizeRaw->{1376, 386},
  PlotRange->{{0, 1376}, {0, 386}}]], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{3.7569118106176853`*^9},
 FontFamily->"Verdana",
 FontWeight->"Regular",ExpressionUUID->"5f6e73cd-e3ca-4000-9901-4014a73c23d6"],

Cell["\<\
Generally speaking, it is a good idea to allow your new function to be \
normalized when dealing only with pixels, and also in the case when you are \
using a grid of points with \[OpenCurlyQuote]real\[CloseCurlyQuote] units. It \
is also a good idea when writing your two-dimensional fft function to allow \
it to act on three-dimensional tensors. This means that the grid shifting \
functionality must act on dimension 1 and 2 but not on higher dimensions.

Once you have written these functions, answer the following questions and \
demonstrate the following requirements:\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.756911973147913*^9, 3.756912012598008*^9}, {
  3.756912599811194*^9, 3.7569126096622334`*^9}, {3.7569130278509293`*^9, 
  3.7569131394788933`*^9}, {3.756913945007506*^9, 3.756913946084997*^9}, {
  3.757002947868967*^9, 
  3.757002950289598*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"e9617e3b-79a2-4e6e-9a2c-\
27c81e052edd"],

Cell[TextData[{
 StyleBox["Demonstrate:",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 "\n\nProve that your FFT conserves power in a Parseval\[CloseCurlyQuote]s \
manner when using a grid of pixels and when using a grid with pixels in \
\[OpenCurlyQuote]real\[CloseCurlyQuote] units, such as microns\n\n",
 StyleBox["Showing output from the command window is fine in both cases",
  FontSize->14,
  FontWeight->"Bold"]
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.756917921507002*^9, 3.7569180436225147`*^9}, 
   3.756919718477096*^9, {3.756957460464983*^9, 3.75695747653386*^9}},
 Background->RGBColor[
  0.87, 0.94, 1],ExpressionUUID->"ab4edc01-509a-4c02-bda8-6488fbb2245f"],

Cell[TextData[{
 StyleBox["Questions:\n",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 "\n1) Take the 2D FFT of a matrix of constant values (such as ones(N)). \
Because the analytically calculated Fourier transform of a constant is a \
Dirac delta function, your 2D FFT should result in a matrix of zeros with one \
non-zero pixel. Explain this behavior in light of the fact that the FFT is a \
discrete Fourier transform and cannot return a true Dirac delta function \
i.e., what function is actually being plotted?\n\n2) Where is the location of \
the one non-zero pixel (written in terms of the number of pixels in your \
grid) if you started with ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"N", " ", "\[Element]", " ", "Even"}]],ExpressionUUID->
  "d9b2fee3-540d-4b41-b239-aab0ec27d50d"],
 "?"
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.756913218572193*^9, 3.756913417769919*^9}, {
   3.7569134522796803`*^9, 3.756913452407228*^9}, {3.756913911016591*^9, 
   3.756913949502693*^9}, {3.756917837965818*^9, 3.756917904771009*^9}, {
   3.756918075232458*^9, 3.7569180755353737`*^9}, {3.7569197419798203`*^9, 
   3.7569197606399107`*^9}, {3.75692034385299*^9, 3.756920376534528*^9}, 
   3.756957365242867*^9, {3.756957645709695*^9, 3.756957646390977*^9}},
 Background->RGBColor[
  0.87, 0.94, 1],ExpressionUUID->"d4bba7a6-dcd8-45f5-a005-86674c84e268"],

Cell[TextData[StyleBox["1.3 Matrix multiplication form of the numerical \
Fourier transform",
 FontWeight->"Bold"]], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.756557377230928*^9, 3.756557446978877*^9}, {
  3.756557556914289*^9, 3.756557562958906*^9}, {3.756557729260766*^9, 
  3.75655773004984*^9}, {3.756560677467579*^9, 3.756560709503097*^9}, {
  3.756578002528997*^9, 3.756578003755828*^9}, {3.7565797893675756`*^9, 
  3.756579832248715*^9}, {3.7565805268351316`*^9, 3.756580544887636*^9}, {
  3.756585707122959*^9, 3.756585712261675*^9}, {3.756587825498391*^9, 
  3.756587825897016*^9}, {3.7568195942862673`*^9, 3.7568195992342377`*^9}, {
  3.7568354241613703`*^9, 3.756835464506969*^9}, {3.756836570393556*^9, 
  3.756836618154336*^9}, {3.756837118072761*^9, 3.7568371181396513`*^9}, {
  3.756919589876535*^9, 3.756919615248456*^9}},
 FontSize->14,
 FontWeight->"Regular",ExpressionUUID->"fb1b5112-097d-44e8-a130-232d524f79ec"],

Cell[TextData[StyleBox["PART I: numerical 2D Fourier transform",
 FontWeight->"Bold"]], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.756835454922119*^9, 3.756835459865612*^9}, 
   3.7568366206401987`*^9, {3.756837079453977*^9, 3.756837088732882*^9}, 
   3.756837120309087*^9},ExpressionUUID->"ad7cd67b-d550-4591-a318-\
e5914c281c50"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "In this exercise you will calculate the shift between two identical (but \
shifted) functions with \[OpenCurlyQuote]sub-pixel\[CloseCurlyQuote] \
accuracy. You will use the fact that the cross-correlation between two \
shifted functions ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"g", "(", 
     RowBox[{"x", ",", "y"}], ")"}], "\[FivePointedStar]", " ", 
    RowBox[{"g", "(", 
     RowBox[{
      RowBox[{"x", "-", 
       SubscriptBox["x", "0"]}], ",", 
      RowBox[{"y", "-", 
       SubscriptBox["y", "0"]}]}], ")"}]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "8ea4512a-5e37-4424-8ea3-9bf52296ebe9"],
 " has a peak at ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"x", "=", 
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{
      RowBox[{
       SubscriptBox["x", "0"], " ", "&"}], " ", "y"}], "=", 
     SubscriptBox["y", "0"]}]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "c4f6c5c2-91bb-4b33-974f-98c737da3f2f"],
 ", for instance in one-dimension and for real functions:\n\n\t",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{"g", "(", "x", ")"}], "\[FivePointedStar]", " ", 
     RowBox[{"g", "(", 
      RowBox[{"x", "-", 
       SubscriptBox["x", "0"]}], ")"}], 
     RowBox[{"(", "x", ")"}]}], "=", 
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{
      SubsuperscriptBox["\[Integral]", 
       RowBox[{"-", "\[Infinity]"}], "\[Infinity]"], " ", 
      RowBox[{
       SuperscriptBox["\[ExponentialE]", 
        RowBox[{
         RowBox[{"-", 
          SuperscriptBox[
           SuperscriptBox["x", "\[Prime]"], "2"]}], "/", 
         SuperscriptBox["\[Sigma]", "2"]}]], 
       SuperscriptBox["\[ExponentialE]", 
        RowBox[{
         RowBox[{"-", 
          SuperscriptBox[
           RowBox[{"(", 
            RowBox[{
             SuperscriptBox["x", "\[Prime]"], "+", "x", "-", 
             SubscriptBox["x", "0"]}], ")"}], "2"]}], "/", 
         SuperscriptBox["\[Sigma]", "2"]}]], 
       RowBox[{"\[DifferentialD]", 
        SuperscriptBox["x", "\[Prime]"]}]}]}], "=", 
     RowBox[{
      SqrtBox[
       FractionBox[
        RowBox[{"\[Pi]", " ", 
         SuperscriptBox["\[Sigma]", "2"]}], "2"]], 
      SuperscriptBox["\[ExponentialE]", 
       RowBox[{"-", 
        FractionBox[
         SuperscriptBox[
          RowBox[{"(", 
           RowBox[{"x", "-", 
            SubscriptBox["x", "0"]}], ")"}], "2"], 
         RowBox[{"2", " ", 
          SuperscriptBox["\[Sigma]", "2"]}]]}]]}]}]}], TraditionalForm]],
  ExpressionUUID->"a884772b-6734-4ad3-9945-44c89ef876ee"],
 "\n\nwhich is a wider Gaussian centered at ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["x", "0"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "d7a82799-2b6e-4010-8e12-38399a80c373"],
 ". As you know, it is possible to calculate cross-correlations is using \
Fourier transforms and the correlation theorem:\n\n\t",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"\[ScriptCapitalF]", 
     RowBox[{"{", 
      RowBox[{
       RowBox[{"g", "(", "x", ")"}], "\[FivePointedStar]", " ", 
       RowBox[{"f", "(", "x", ")"}]}], "}"}]}], "=", 
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{
      OverscriptBox["G", "~"], "(", 
      SubscriptBox["f", "x"], ")"}], 
     RowBox[{
      SuperscriptBox[
       OverscriptBox["F", "~"], "*"], "(", 
      SubscriptBox["f", "x"], ")"}]}]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "650d464e-6afa-47c9-8c5d-d030f77c6267"],
 "\n\nwe can take the inverse Fourier transform of this to give the \
cross-correlation\n\n\t",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{"g", "(", "x", ")"}], "\[FivePointedStar]", " ", 
     RowBox[{"f", "(", "x", ")"}]}], "=", 
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{
      SuperscriptBox["\[ScriptCapitalF]", 
       RowBox[{"-", "1"}]], 
      RowBox[{"{", 
       RowBox[{
        RowBox[{
         OverscriptBox["G", "~"], "(", 
         SubscriptBox["f", "x"], ")"}], 
        RowBox[{
         SuperscriptBox[
          OverscriptBox["F", "~"], "*"], "(", 
         SubscriptBox["f", "x"], ")"}]}], "}"}]}], "=", 
     RowBox[{
      SuperscriptBox["\[ScriptCapitalF]", 
       RowBox[{"-", "1"}]], 
      RowBox[{"{", 
       RowBox[{"\[ScriptCapitalF]", 
        RowBox[{"{", 
         RowBox[{"g", "(", "x", ")"}], "}"}], "\[ScriptCapitalF]", 
        SuperscriptBox[
         RowBox[{"{", 
          RowBox[{"f", "(", "x", ")"}], "}"}], "*"]}], "}"}]}]}]}], 
   TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->"8b6db9fa-18e8-4c93-a66c-211e78502353"],
 "\n\nOne prescription is then to 1) take the Fourier transform of both the \
shifted and unshifted functions 2) conjugate one of the functions 3) Take the \
product of the conjugated and un-conjugated Fourier transforms and 4) inverse \
Fourier transform to calculate the cross-correlation.\n\nTo find the relative \
shift, simply locate the peak of the resulting cross-correlation.\n\nThe key \
to obtaining \[OpenCurlyQuote]sub-pixel\[CloseCurlyQuote] accuracy is to \
perform the full prescription using FFTs the first time to determine the \
shift to within one pixel (use your newly written, normalized FFT routines). \
Then repeat the process but in the final inverse Fourier transform (step 4 in \
the prescription) use a numerical Fourier transform that is \
\[OpenCurlyQuote]zoomed\[CloseCurlyQuote] in on the peak position with many \
more pixels, thereby increasing the resolution of the peak-finding operation.\
\n\nYou COULD use the non-uniform Fourier transform that you wrote in \
\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]",
 StyleBox["1.1 Summation form of the numerical Fourier transform (AKA \
nonuniform discrete Fourier transform)",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 "\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] HOWEVER! This would require writing loops and \
performing this operation for every column/row in both directions. Much \
nicer, is to define grids where you need to calculate the Fourier transform \
and then construct two matrices. The first matrix, when multiplied by an \
image, will calculate the nonuniform inverse Fourier transform of the \
columns. When the resulting image is multiplied by your second matrix, the \
two-dimensional, nonuniform inverse Fourier transform will be the result.\n\n\
Locate the peak in the \[OpenCurlyQuote]zoomed\[CloseCurlyQuote], upsampled \
image, this will be the sub-pixel portion of the shift. Then relate that \
location back to the \[OpenCurlyQuote]un-zoomed\[CloseCurlyQuote] coordinates \
to calculate the full shift value including sub-pixel components. An example \
of the process in pictures is shown below:"
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.75683547774187*^9, 3.756835621448901*^9}, {
   3.756835673915987*^9, 3.756835742373774*^9}, {3.756835778849819*^9, 
   3.756835981189065*^9}, {3.7568361963759527`*^9, 3.756836214799802*^9}, {
   3.7568362949807777`*^9, 3.7568363895725927`*^9}, {3.756836440886755*^9, 
   3.756836511873605*^9}, {3.756836833203177*^9, 3.756836843204282*^9}, {
